rch in the tumultuous region, to ongoing politicized pressures from colleagues, students, and outside groups, to hurdles in sharing expertise with the public. They detail how academia, even within anthropology, an assumed "liberal" discipline, is infused with sexism, racism, Islamophobia, and Zionist obstruction of any criticism of the Israeli state. Anthropology's Politics offers a complex portrait of how academic politics ultimately hinders the education of U.S. students and potentially limits the public's access to critical knowledge about the Middle East.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aAnthropologyxPolitical aspectsxMiddle East. 0aAnthropologyxPolitical aspectszMiddle East. 0aUniversities and collegesxPolitical aspectsxUnited States. 0aUniversities and collegesxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 4aIslamophobia. 4aMiddle East. 4aPalestine. 4aWar on Terror. 4aanthropology. 4agender. 4ahigher education. 4ainstitutions. 4aneoliberalism. 4arace/ethnicity. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aWinegar, Jessica, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479684240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804796842423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804796842.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles